> I would like the ability to inject a resource (typically a script) at a particular point in the page flow in order to enable me to instrument. However:
> - onPageInitialized fires before the script my instrumentation depends on (e.g. &quot;qunit.js&quot;) has been loaded
> - both injectJs and includeJs add scripts to the bottom of the page and/or after the page has already fully loaded
> 
> For example, if I wanted to add instrumentation (specifically for reporting with PhantomJS) before I execute my QUnit tests:
>     &lt;script type=&quot;text/javascript&quot; src=&quot;/js/qunit.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
>     **\* INJECT INSTRUMENTATION SCRIPT HERE ***
>     &lt;script type=&quot;text/javascript&quot; src=&quot;/js/runMyQunitTests.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
> 
> I could theoretically modify a request URL during a &quot;page.onResourceRequested&quot; handler to point to a different resource but that means I'd have to have some sort of mechanism for bundled my instrumentation plus whatever resource I actually wanted (assuming that resource is also JavaScript, as I can't add my JS to an CSS/image/etc. file).
> 
> I'm curious if it would be possible to implement this now (again, only for JavaScript resource requests) by altering the incoming request URL to be a Data URI instead? For example:
> 
> page.onResourceRequested = function(request) {
>     if (request.url.indexOf(&quot;/js/qunit.js&quot;) &gt; -1) {
>         var fs = require(&quot;fs&quot;),
>             dataUrlPrefix = &quot;data:text/javascript;charset=utf-8,&quot;,
>             dataRequested = fs.read(&quot;/js/qunit.js&quot;),
>             dataAfter = fs.read(&quot;/js/phantom-qunit.js&quot;);
>         request.url = dataUrlPrefix + dataRequested + dataAfter;
>     }
> };
> 
> As you can see, the above depends on me reading the requested file from the filesystem myself as PhantomJS can't synchronously download files from the web [that I'm aware of]. This may rarely be the actual situation, so this isn't very ideal either.
> 
> Alternatively, if we had access to the resource response body [related issue: http://code.google.com/p/phantomjs/issues/detail?id=158 ], you could potentially alter it much more easily that way without needing the actual requested resource present on the local filesystem (as in the above example). For example:
> 
> page.onResourceReceived = function(response) {
>     if (response.url.indexOf(&quot;qunit.js&quot;) &gt; -1) {
>         var fs = require(&quot;fs&quot;),
>             rawScript = fs.read(&quot;/js/phantom-qunit.js&quot;);
>         response.text += &quot;document.write('&lt;script&gt;' + rawScript + '&lt;/script&gt;');
>     }
> };
> 
> All that said, I feel like this functionality is worthy of an actual API as well... I'm just not sure what it would be. Perhaps it's not feasible given the asynchronous nature of the resource loading, though.

